<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>_x0001_ wwwpatientsfirst</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from Patients First (GMC0015)</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 35.5pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Patients First is a network of NHS whistleblowers and supporters who purpose is to reduce death and harm in the NHS by campaigning for the UK Government to create policies and laws that ensure the NHS becomes open and accountable and we will actively support all those who raise concerns about patient safety</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 35.5pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">(1) Patients  First has concerns that the General Medical Council has a poor understanding of the nature of raising concerns and does not in its system and processes, adequately take note of whistleblowers information or take active steps to support and protect them from </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">victimisation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 35.5pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Summary and recommendation</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 64.02pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Patients First is concerned that not enough note is taken of information provided to the GMC by a medical or nursing whistleblower, and we have raised this with them. It takes great courage to step forward with concerns about a fellow clinician and the least we can hope for is that the information that we as whistleblowers are willing to provide is of interest to the regulator. We believe in a number of cases that the information that the whistleblower was party to would have made a significant difference to the GMC understanding of the case, and could have impacted upon the outcome.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 64.02pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Patients First has met with the General medical Council a number of times and has highlighted how an employer can victimize a doctor by making a referral to them on “trumped up charges” in effect. We have offered to help them review such cases, and assist in developing other ways of assessing referrals from employers so that patient safety is protected. The emotional impact upon individuals who have followed their professional duty is immense and we are very concerned that the impact is life changing for such individuals. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 64.02pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We have offered to share these case studies with the GMC and they to date have not shown any interest in hearing from us in this regard. We recommend that there is learning from such cases, to prevent unnecessary harm to whistleblowers.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 64.02pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Patients First believes that in high profile cases where patient safety has failed and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">whistleblowing</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> policy has been clearly breached the GMC could be more pro active. The GMC could act swiftly  in holding any doctor to account who has victimized a whistleblower or suppressed the truth, either through hiding or editing documents or attempting to gag a whistleblower.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 64.02pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Patients First request that any registered medical practitioner is unable to remove themselves from the register when holding positions of responsibility for patients. By doing do they can evade taking responsibility for decisions that impacted upon patient safety. There are often important lessons to be learned by a hearing of decisions taken regards to a service and this opportunity can be lost by allowing those responsible to walk away.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 64.02pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We also recommend that the GMC abandon the five year rule, because many cases of attempted cover ups take many years to unravel and in the meantime those who could be held to account can cite the 5 year rule in their </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">defence</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, escape accountability, and that is wrong.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 64.02pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Patient Safety is so important and the protection of whistleblowers is at </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">he</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> heart of this that we hope that the Committee will seek clarification on the above issues, and what steps the GMC are planning to take to remedy these. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 64.02pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We propose that the victimization of a whistleblower should be a “never event”, and we would be hopeful that the GMC would take very step to prevent such occurrences</span></li></ul><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 71.5pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Submission</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 107.5pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">1)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In the case of Patients First founder Dr Kim Holt 2955126 who </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">whistleblew</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> with regard to the understaffing and administration issues at St Ann’s Hospital </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Haringey</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, she raised these system issues with the GMC in the post baby P time before she was openly acknowledged as a whistleblower.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 107.5pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Despite numerous attempts to notify the GMC of the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Haringey</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> health system issues, the GMC appeared to dismiss or take account of these in the case of Dr Al </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Zayyat</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 107.5pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">3)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Dr Al </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Zayyat</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,  became suicidal through the process of her fitness to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">pratice</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> hearings. </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 107.5pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">4)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">A significant amount of her distress was the manner in which she was referred to the GMC by her employer and that she felt used as a scapegoat.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 107.5pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">5)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="background-color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Nurse Ms L Blackburn</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> was a whistleblower in the case of </span><span style="background-color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Dr </span><span style="background-color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Hickstep</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> a GP in Oxford and she was not given a chance to be interviewed by the case examiners at the time that </span><span style="background-color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Dr </span><span style="background-color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Hickstep’s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> case was being looked at. Ms Blackburn lost her job having raised her concerns about </span><span style="background-color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Dr </span><span style="background-color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Hicksteps</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> practice, and she feels that the least the GMC could have done is to have listened to her detailed evidence whilst his case was being looked at by the GMC.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 107.5pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">6)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The most famous case of a doctor being referred to the GMC having raised patient safety concerns is that of Dr Raj </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Mattu</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, a consultant cardiologist. He was reportedly referred to the GMC with over a hundred allegations, all subsequently proven to be wrong. In the meantime he was subjected to huge emotional pressure, and this affected his health badly. He remains out of his post and has endured many years of legal battles to try and protect his name.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 107.5pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">7)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">There are however other cases of doctors who have been referred to the GMC following raising of concerns and we believe that a full inquiry into these cases needs to happen so that there can be steps taken to prevent this happening in the future.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 107.5pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">8)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">There are a number of high profile cases, where there have been serious failures of patient care and where doctors should have been more responsive to early warnings. </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 107.5pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">9)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We submit that in the examples of Community </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">paediatric</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> services, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Haringey</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, maternity services at </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Morecambe</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Bay, Warnings at Stafford hospital, the GMC should have looked into the roles of responsible medical practitioners, and should be more ready to hold these individuals to account for failures to protect patient safety, and act in a pro active way rather than await referrals from elsewhere.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 107.5pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">10)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Finally Dr Jane Collins ex Chief executive of Great Ormond Street hospital removed herself from the GMC register in 2010, when the scandal of the alleged cover up over baby P death was in the press. This has prevented a fitness to practice hearing regards her involvement in the editing of the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Sibert</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> report being possible. There is clear evidence that Dr Collins edited the report, and removed the references to the service being clinically risky or of “grave concern” to the investigators. Being able to remove oneself from the register in this way seems wrong.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">(2) The refusal of the General Medical Council to accept any referrals regarding Fitness for Practice of senior medical managers in respect of their acts and omissions as lead doctors</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Summary and recommendation</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Patients First believes the General Medical Council is failing to ensure compliance with its own ethical code </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Good Medical Practice</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and its guidance </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Leadership and Management for All Doctors </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">by its insistence in response to referrals about medical managers and leaders that the GMC “can only consider issues that would raise concerns about an individual doctor’s fitness to practise.” The response to well evidenced referrals expressing serious concerns about the acts and omissions of three senior medical managers at ATOS risks fundamentally undermining the professional accountability of senior medical leaders and managers. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It would be helpful for the Committee to seek urgent clarification as to GMC policy on this important matter and to consider in any recommendations the urgent need to revise the current policy.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Submission</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 49.5pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Patients First has serious concerns about the refusal of the GMC to hold to account those doctors leading ATOS, a company </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">contracted on behalf of the DWP to carry out Work Capability Assessments for people applying for the sickness benefit Employment and Support Allowance (ESA. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 49.5pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We believe senior doctors with management responsibilities at ATOS might have failed to comply with </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Good Medical Practice</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">56. You must give priority to patients on the basis of their clinical need if these decisions are within your power. If inadequate resources, policies or systems prevent you from doing this, and patient safety, dignity or comfort may be seriously compromised, you must follow the guidance in </span><a href="http://www.gmc-uk.org/guidance/good_medical_practice/respond_to_risks.asp"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">paragraph 25b</span></a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 49.5pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We noted that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">whistleblower Dr Greg Wood </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">aid</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> he had resigned from working for ATOS because</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 72pt; text-indent:3pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">"I was instructed to change my reports, to reduce the number of points that might be awarded to the claimants. I felt that was wrong professionally and ethically.”</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (</span><a href="http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-22546036"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-22546036</span></a><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">5. If Dr Wood’s allegations were correct (and we believe they are) then there would appear to be a prima facie case for considering whether the senior ATOS medical leaders might have breached Paragraphs 56, 24 and 25 b and c of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Good Medical Practice</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> which state</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 7.5pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">24. You must promote and encourage a culture that allows all staff to raise concerns openly and safely. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">25. You must take prompt action if you think that patient safety, dignity or comfort is or may be seriously compromised.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 71.5pt"><a href="http://www.gmc-uk.org/guidance/good_medical_practice/respond_to_risks.asp"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.gmc-uk.org/guidance/good_medical_practice/respond_to_risks.asp</span></a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 49.5pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ATOS  accept their work is of a clinical nature:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">"Our role in the process is to do an assessment, gather the medical evidence and write a report that goes to the department, upon which they can gather more evidence and make a decision."</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">"Clinical judgement is the foundation of our part of the Work Capability Assessment process. We send the DWP independent, clinically justified reports to help the department's decision makers make a decision on benefit entitlement...”</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 49.5pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ATOS says its doctors must:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">be registered with the General Medical Council (GMC)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">have 3 years broad-based clinical post-registration experience </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">achieve approval (post training) from the CMA in the appropriate benefit.</span></li></ul><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 49.5pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">The GMC has confirmed that doctors making ATOS WCA assessments are subject to the GMC’s ethical principles and accountability framework:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“Edward Cooper is mistaken that the principle of making the care of your patients does not apply to doctors when they are assessing </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">benefits claimants on behalf of ATOS. Our guidance is for all doctors and in the guidance we use the term ‘patient’ to refer to anyone whom doctors test, treat or assess in their professional capacity as a doctor. This includes amongst others, employees, benefits and insurance claimants, and athletes.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 72pt"><a href="http://www.gmc.uk.org/Confidentiality_disclosing_info_insurance_2009.pdf_27493823.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.gmc.uk.org/Confidentiality_disclosing_info_insurance_2009.pdf_27493823.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">(</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">BMJ </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">2011;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">342:d1155)</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.5pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The GMC makes clear in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Leadership and management for all </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">that </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">“16 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Whether you have a management role or not, your primary duty is to</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">patients. Their care, dignity and safety must be your first concern. You</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">also have a duty to the health of the wider community, your profession,</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">your colleagues and the organisation in which you work.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.5pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This guidance clarifies these statements of principle:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“Although these principles are relevant to all doctors, whatever roles they have, the judgment in Remedy UK Ltd, R (on the application of Remedy UK Ltd) v General Medical Council [2010] EWHC 1245 (Admin) found that there are some roles that are so far removed from practising medicine that the GMC’s fitness to practise procedures do not apply to them. However, doctors are still accountable to the GMC when they are performing a wide range of clinical management roles (for example, as a clinical or medical director) or other non-clinical roles (for example, as a medical educator or researcher), even if medical knowledge or expertise is not needed for the roles (for example, as a chief executive of a hospital</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">).”</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 72pt"><a href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/healthnews/10074192/Judges-rule-back-to-work-assessments-unfair-to-mentally-ill.html"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/healthnews/10074192/Judges-rule-back-to-work-assessments-unfair-to-mentally-ill.html</span></a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 49.5pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Our referral made detailed reference to evidence supporting our referral and to concerns from other doctors, those assessed by ATOS doctors and nurses and various Parliamentary Select Committee reports about the nature and reliability of the medical assessments overseen by three senior doctors who either are currently working for, or have worked in the recent past for, ATOS, during the period that the concerns raised in our complaint:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 66.02pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Dr Laura Crawford</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, the Clinical Director within </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Atos</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Healthcare responsible for the medical aspects of their work on the Medical Services Contract with DWP. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 66.02pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Professor Michael O'Donnell</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, the Chief Medical Officer of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Atos</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Healthcare,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> responsible for Oversight of Professional Standards and Clinical Governance in both the Occupational Health and Medical Services side. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 66.02pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Dr Angela Graham</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, Assistant Medical Director, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Atos</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Healthcare</span></li></ul><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 53.5pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Our referral was not about the individual clinical roles of these three doctors: </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Our complaint is whether, in the light of the systematic and publicly recorded evidence of standards which appear to undermine the ethical standards expected of medical managers and leaders of these processes, they should be held to account for not upholding the ethical standards which are a prerequisite of their registration as medical practitioners relies on. In particular we believe that all the healthcare practitioners are required to show the same level of competency and professional duty towards their patients and clients as their peers working in other healthcare organisations and that the three practitioners about whom we raise concerns had a duty to ensure that was the case and have a case to answer that they failed in that duty.</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 53.5pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We believe the refusal of the GMC to apparently even consider whether the wider medical management and leadership responsibilities of doctors can be subject to a Fitness to Practice referral is dangerous and a breach of the ethical principles the GMC states it seeks to apply to the profession</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 53.5pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">On August 23rd 203 the GMC response to our original referral of May27th 2013 and our later supporting evidence. It stated: </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">We have reviewed your letter about ATOS and the doctors who have held senior management roles there. We have also reviewed the decision of the Court in the Remedy UK case. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">We have concluded that at present we have no evidence or information raising specific fitness to practise concerns of any of the doctors identified. As such the GMC cannot investigate the matter further under our fitness to practise procedures and we will be taking no further action at present.</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 53.5pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">On behalf of Patients First, Roger Kline sought clarification as why they h\d reached this decision and asked if the GMC would clarify whether it accepted </span></li></ol><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 86pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">that Good Medical Practice was applicable to the work of the medical workforce in conducting assessments?</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 86pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">that Good Medical Practice was breached in numerous individual cases in the reported practice of ATOS medical staff?</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 36pt 0pt 86pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">that the individual doctors I referred were the line managers and clinical leaders of those responsible for the practices that took place?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 36pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 53.5pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">He asked whether on the basis of this decision the GMC could envisage whether there would be </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">any</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> grounds on which to report and admonish these who clinical and managerially led the widely reported poor practices at ATOS even if it were accepted that the appalling reported practices took place? His letter continued:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Applying your logic to Mid Staffordshire or any other hospital, can you clarify whether this means, as it appears to do, that any failing by registered medical leaders to set appropriate standards, to ensure the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">work of their staff was monitored and appraised, to ensure that the standards to be followed met the requirements within Good Medical Practice, or to fail to act on public reports of unsafe or inappropriate practice, would not (could not) be the basis of any investigation by the GMC unless it could be demonstrated the individual hands on medical practice of senior managers who may never undertake direct care, or whose own direct care is deemed appropriate would excuse them from investigation? </span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 53.5pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">On 11 September 2013 the Fitness to Practice Directorate closed the correspondence by simply stating in response that </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Please be advised that we can’t consider any matters related to ATOS as an organisation. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">We can only consider issues that would raise concerns about an individual doctor’s fitness to practise. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">As there have been no specific concerns raised about a doctor we are not able to assist you with this matter at present. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 13pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 13pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 13pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>